HEADWORD: Perigeum
<hw>Per`i*ge"um</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>perigeum</ets>, fr.
Gr. <grk>peri`</grk> about, near + <grk>gh^</grk> the earth: cf. F.
<ets>p⟦eacute⟧rig⟦eacute⟧e</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>That
point, in the orbit of the moon or other body orbiting the earth, which
is nearest to the earth; -- opposed to <ant>apogee</ant>. It is
sometimes, but rarely, used of the nearest points of bodies not orbiting
the earth, such as of a comet, a planet, etc. Called also
<altname>epigee</altname>, <altname>epigeum</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

